Association Rules

Association Rules: Notes from Data Science and Big Data Analytics from Wiley.

Confidence is defined as the measure of the certainty or trustworthiness associated with each discovered rule. Confidence is the percent of transactions that contain both \(X\) and \(Y\) out of all the transactions that contain \(X\).

\[ Confidence(X\rightarrow Y) = \frac{Support(X\wedge Y)}{Support(X)} \]

When you set a minimum confidence, you are choosing to ignore confidence levels between a certain threshold.

Lift measures how many times more often and Y occur together than expected if they are statistically independent of each other. Lift is a measure of how X and Y are really related rather than coincidentally happening together.

\[ Lift(X \rightarrow Y) = \frac{Support(X\wedge Y)}{Support(X)^*Support(Y)} \]

Lift is 1 if X and Y are statistically independent of each other. In contrast, a lift of \(X\rightarrow Y\) greater than 1 indicates that there is some usefulness to the rule. A larger value of lift suggests a greater strengh of the association between X and Y.

For example, if \(\{ bread, eggs, milk \}\) has support of .15 and \(\{ bread, eggs \}\) also has a support of .15, the confidence of rule \(\{ bread, eggs \} \rightarrow \{milk \}\) is 1. Assuming 1000 transactions, with \(\{bread, eggs \}\) in 200 of them, \(\{ eggs \}\) in 100 of them and \(\{ bread \}\) in 300 of them, the Lift is \(\frac{.2}{.1^* .3} \approx 67\%\)

Leverage measures the difference in the probability of \(X\) and \(Y\) appearing together in the dataset compared to what would be expected if \(X\) and \(Y\) were statistically independent of each other.

\[ Leverage(X \rightarrow Y) = Support(X\wedge Y)\: - Support(X)^*Support(Y) \]

In theory, leverage is 0 when \(X\) and \(Y\) are statistically independednt of each other. If \(X\) and \(Y\) have some kind of relationship, the leverage would be greater than 0. A larger leverage value indicates a stronger relationship between X and Y. Confidence is able to identify trustworthy rules, but it cannot tell whether a rule is conincidental. A high-confidence reule can sometimes be misleading because confidence does not consider support of the itemset in the rule consequent.

Applications of Association Rules:

  • Broad-scale approaches to better merchandising what products should be included in or excluded from the invectory each month.
  • Cross-merchandising between products and high-margin or high-ticket items.
  • Physical or logical placement of product within related categories of products.
  • Promotional programs multiple product purchase incentives managed through a loyalty card program.

In the dataset Groceries@data, the columns represent a transaction and the rows represent particular items (denoted by TRUE) that have been purchased. The items purchased correspond to the dataset Groceries@itemIfo, which is a list of specific items. So, to determine which items person in column 10 purchased, you can use the command Groceries@itemInfo[Groceries@data[,10],1]

apply(Groceries@data[,1:20], 2, function(r) paste(Groceries@itemInfo[r, "labels"], collapse=", "))

In the next iteration, the list of 1-itemsets is joined onto itself to form all possible candidate 2-itemsets. For example, 1-itemsets \(\{whole milk \}\) and \(\{soda \}\) would be joined to become a 2-itemset \(\{whole\: milk, soda \}\). The algoritm computes the support of each candidate 2-itemset and retains those that satisfy the minimum support.

itemsets <- apriori(Groceries, parameter=list(minlen=2, maxlen = 2, support = .02, target = "frequent itemsets"))

The apriori function can also be used to generate rules. Assume that the minimum support threshold is not set to a lower value 0.001, and the minimum confidence threshold is set to 0.6. A lower miniimum suppport threshold allows more rules to show up. The following ode creates 2918 rules from all the tranactionsin the Groceries dataset.

rules <- apriori(Groceries, parameter=list(support=0.001, confidence = 0.6, target = "rules"))

Support algorithm for 1-itemsets only.

apriorifdRen <- function(data, namesList, minSupport) {

     nTransactions <- ncol(data)
     # sup is shorthand for support
     sup <- nTransactions*minSupport
     
     # Count how many times each item occurs in the dataset
     itemVec <- vector()
     for(col in 1:ncol(data)) {
          itemVec <- append(itemVec, which(data[,col]))
     }

     itemVec <- table(itemVec)
     itemVec <- itemVec[itemVec >= sup]
     names(itemVec) <- Groceries@itemInfo[,1][as.integer(names(itemVec))]
     sort(itemVec, decreasing = TRUE)/nTransactions
}

itemVec <- apriorifdRen(data = Groceries@data,sort(itemVec, decreasing = TRUE)/ncol(Groceries@data), minSupport = .02)
